%I A395624 #8 Jun 10 2026 15:41:59
%S A395624 7,-31,-108,-256,-311,-500,-864,-3408,-6660,-15760,-16384,19716,
%T A395624 -23328,-27436,-49800,-117156,-146328,-167728,-276848,-498204,-685720,
%U A395624 -864272,-1166928,-1588812,-1747584,-2291100,-2480112,-2623720,-3452640,-3675732,-5026016,-5838404,-6009380
%N A395624 a(n) = round(1/(b(n) - round(b(n)))), where b(n) = sqrt(k) + sqrt(m) with k = A395621(n) and positive nonsquare m < k minimizing the distance of b(n) from the nearest integer.
%C A395624 A395621 lists nonsquare values k for which {sqrt(k) + sqrt(m); 0 < m < k, m not a square} has smaller distance from the integers than for all smaller nonsquare k > m > 0. This sequence lists the inverse of that distance, rounded to the nearest integer, with minus sign whenever the closest sqrt(k) + sqrt(m) is to the left of the nearest integer.
%e A395624 A395621(1) = 3 (the least nonsquare number k for which there exists a smaller positive nonsquare number m, namely 2), and sqrt(3) + sqrt(2) = 3.146... which is at distance 0.146... ~ 1/7 from the integers, hence a(1) = 7 = round(1/0.146...).
%e A395624 A395621(2) = 5, the next larger nonsquare number k for which there exists a smaller positive nonsquare number m, namely 3), such that sqrt(5) + sqrt(3) = 3.968... is closer to the nearest integer than the previous sum sqrt(3)+sqrt(2); hence a(1) = round(1/(3.968... - 4)) = round(-1/0.03188...) = -31. The minus sign shows that sqrt(5) + sqrt(3) is to the left of the nearest integer, 4.
%o A395624 (PARI) A395624(n, k=A395621[n])=my(r=sqrt(k), b, d=oo);for(m=1,k-1,my(t=sqrt(m)+r);abs(t-round(t))<d && d=abs(t-round(b=t)));1\/(b-round(b)) \\ requires a predefined vector A395621 of initial values of that sequence; alternatively, A395621(n) can be otherwise specified as second (optional) argument, in which case the first argument (n) is ignored.
%Y A395624 Cf. A395621.
%K A395624 sign,new
%O A395624 1,1
%A A395624 _M. F. Hasler_, Jun 03 2026
